{"id":"2102.06983","submitter":"Pavel Shumyatsky","authors":"Eloisa Detomi, Pavel Shumyatsky","title":"On the commuting probability for subgroups of a finite group","comments":"The earlier version has been considerably modified. Essentially, the\n  present version is a new paper","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $K$ be a subgroup of a finite group $G$. The probability that an element\nof $G$ commutes with an element of $K$ is denoted by $Pr(K,G)$. Assume that\n$Pr(K,G)\\geq\\epsilon$ for some fixed $\\epsilon>0$. We show that there is a\nnormal subgroup $T\\leq G$ and a subgroup $B\\leq K$ such that the indexes\n$[G:T]$ and $[K:B]$ and the order of the commutator subgroup $[T,B]$ are\n$\\epsilon$-bounded. This extends the well known theorem, due to P. M. Neumann,\nthat covers the case where $K=G$.\n  We deduce a number of corollaries of this result. A typical application is\nthat if $K$ is the generalized Fitting subgroup $F^*(G)$ then $G$ has a\nclass-2-nilpotent normal subgroup $R$ such that both the index $[G:R]$ and the\norder of the commutator subgroup $[R,R]$ are $\\epsilon$-bounded. In the same\nspirit we consider the cases where $K$ is a term of the lower central series of\n$G$, or a Sylow subgroup, etc.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 13 Feb 2021 18:54:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 1 May 2021 18:52:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-04"}
